<div id="understanding-base-estimators" class="section level2">
<h2>4. Understanding Base Estimators</h2>
<p>The <code>doas()</code> function leverages several group-abundance
estimators under the hood. For advanced applications, these are exported
for you to use directly:</p>
<div id="chapman-estimator-independent-observers" class="section level3">
<h3>Chapman Estimator (Independent Observers)</h3>
<p>A bias-adjusted Lincoln-Petersen estimator.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb8"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb8-1"><a href="#cb8-1" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">chapman_estimate</span>(<span class="at">both =</span> <span class="dv">10</span>, <span class="at">obs1_only =</span> <span class="dv">2</span>, <span class="at">obs2_only =</span> <span class="dv">3</span>)</span>
<span id="cb8-2"><a href="#cb8-2" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; [1] 15.54545</span></span>
<span id="cb8-3"><a href="#cb8-3" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">chapman_variance</span>(<span class="at">both =</span> <span class="dv">10</span>, <span class="at">obs1_only =</span> <span class="dv">2</span>, <span class="at">obs2_only =</span> <span class="dv">3</span>)</span>
<span id="cb8-4"><a href="#cb8-4" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; [1] 0.7520661</span></span></code></pre></div>
</div>
<div id="zippin-estimator-dependent-observers" class="section level3">
<h3>Zippin Estimator (Dependent Observers)</h3>
<p>A removal estimator for primary/secondary observer setups.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb9"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb9-1"><a href="#cb9-1" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">dependent_zippin_estimate</span>(<span class="at">both =</span> <span class="dv">10</span>, <span class="at">obs1_only =</span> <span class="dv">2</span>, <span class="at">obs2_only =</span> <span class="dv">3</span>)</span>
<span id="cb9-2"><a href="#cb9-2" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; [1] 16</span></span>
<span id="cb9-3"><a href="#cb9-3" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">dependent_zippin_variance</span>(<span class="at">both =</span> <span class="dv">10</span>, <span class="at">obs1_only =</span> <span class="dv">2</span>, <span class="at">obs2_only =</span> <span class="dv">3</span>)</span>
<span id="cb9-4"><a href="#cb9-4" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; [1] 2.962963</span></span></code></pre></div>
</div>
<div id="bayesian-conjugate-estimator" class="section level3">
<h3>Bayesian Conjugate Estimator</h3>
<p>Uses Monte Carlo simulations to draw from Beta posteriors, naturally
preventing negative estimates and bounding credible intervals.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb10"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb10-1"><a href="#cb10-1" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">set.seed</span>(<span class="dv">123</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-2"><a href="#cb10-2" tabindex="-1"></a>bayesian_res <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">bayesian_conjugate_estimate</span>(<span class="at">both =</span> <span class="dv">10</span>, <span class="at">obs1_only =</span> <span class="dv">2</span>, <span class="at">obs2_only =</span> <span class="dv">3</span>, <span class="at">iter =</span> <span class="dv">1000</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-3"><a href="#cb10-3" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="at">Mean =</span> bayesian_res<span class="sc">$</span>mean, <span class="at">Variance =</span> bayesian_res<span class="sc">$</span>var)</span>
<span id="cb10-4"><a href="#cb10-4" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt;       Mean   Variance </span></span>
<span id="cb10-5"><a href="#cb10-5" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#&gt; 15.6973227  0.2961748</span></span></code></pre></div>
</div>
